It is better perhaps to make the colour (or grey level in this case) update responsible for its own timing.  In the following it is only necessary to call the `FT_print_text_animate()` function at an interval somewhat faster than the required update interval - it handles its own timing, and changes the colour only when it is time to do so:


    #include &lt;time.h&gt;
    #include &lt;stdint.h&gt;

    #define GREY_LEVEL_CHANGE_PERIOD (CLOCKS_PER_SEC / 5)    // Change five time per second (for example)
    
    static void UpdateTextGreyLevel()
    {
        // Levels to cycle back-and forth through
        static const uint32_t grey_levels[] = { 0xFF,0xDC,0xD3,0xC0,0xA9,0x80,0x69 } ;

        // Current grey index and direction through cycle
        static int cycle_index = 0 ;
        static int direction = -1 ;
    
        // Set current grey level
        uint32_t grey_level = grey_levels[cycle_index] ; 
        updatecolor( grey_level &lt;&lt; 16 | grey_level &lt;&lt; 8 | grey_level );
        
        // If it is time to change grey level....
        static clock_t last_change = 0 ;
        clock_t now = clock() ;
        if( now - last_change &gt; GREY_LEVEL_CHANGE_PERIOD )
        {
            // Start new interval
            last_change = now ;

            // Change direction at either end of the cycle
            if( cycle_index == sizeof(grey_levels) - 1 || cycle_index == 0 )
            {
                direction = -direction ;
            }

            // Increment/decrement cycle index
            cycle_index += direction ;
        }
    }

    void FT_print_text_animate( uint dst_x, uint dst_y, const char text )
    {
        UpdateTextGreyLevel() ;
        FT_loop_text( dst_x, dst_y, text, 2 ) ;
    }

For example you may have a main loop:

    for(;;)
    {
        FT_print_text_animate(0, 0, &quot;Hello!&quot; ) ;
    } 

And the grey level will change at 200ms (in this example) intervals regardless. If you are &quot;moving&quot; the text also, then the determination of the position might use a similar _call rate independent_ timing to update the position.

Essentially you call the function as fast as you are able, and let the function determine whether it is time to update anything.  In that way all your timings can be entirely independent of each-other and not reliant on any loop update interval.

To change the number and values of the grey levels, it is only necessary here to change the `grey_levels` array - everything else sorts itself out.

